Formosa, LG International, Puregold, UMC: Asia Ex-Japan Equities Preview

-- B y   A n u c h i t   N g u y e n
-- 
2011-10-04T21:24:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-03/cebu-air-formosa-keppel-malaysia-smelting-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Bank of the Philippine Islands (BPI)  : The nation’s
largest bank by market value was raised to “buy” from “hold”
by Katherine Tan, an analyst ATR KimEng Securities Inc. The
stock declined 1.8 percent to 53.40 pesos.  Formosa Petrochemical Corp. (6505)  (6505 TT): Formosa’s exports of
diesel and fuel oil from its Mailiao refinery have returned to
normal, Lin Keh-yen, a Taipei-based company spokesman, said by
phone. The company expects to process between 400,000 and
420,000 barrels of crude oil a day in October, up from an
average of 380,000 in September, he said. The shares gained 2.4
percent to NT$82.60.  LG International Corp. (001120)  (001120 KS): LG International will
buy an additional 10 percent stake in GeoPark Chile SA for 113.1
billion won ($95 million), according to a regulatory filing. The
stock dropped 8.6 percent to 40,200 won.  Puregold Price Club Inc. (PGOLD PM): The Philippine grocery
store operator will start trading today after completing the
sale of 600 million shares in an initial public offering. The
shares were sold at 12.50 pesos each.  United Microelectronics Corp. (2303)  (2303 TT): United
Microelectronics’ NexPower Technology Corp. affiliate wrote off
NT$1.239 billion from the impairment of assets in the third
quarter, the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based chipmaker said in an exchange
filing. United Microelectronics rose 1.8 percent to NT$11.50.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anuchit Nguyen in Bangkok at 
 anguyen@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at   dboey@bloomberg.net . 